#regram • @multitaskingmombrain A DIY air purifier, who knew?! 
 
#ad The @CorsiRosenthalbox was developed by inventors Jim Rosenthal and Dr. Richard Corsi during a time when there was a high demand for air purification systems. @3M simply wanted to help in this movement! Their scientists concluded that the boxes were effective at capturing unwanted airborne particles including viruses and serve as a good supplement to a more holistic ventilation strategy! 

To date, hundreds of Corsi Rosenthal boxes have been used in schools, businesses and homes around the world, and are a much more affordable option when compared to expensive HEPA filtration systems. 
 
Supplies needed: 
20” box fan 
4- 3M Filtrete MPR 1900/MERV 13 air filters, size 20x20x1”
20” piece of cardboard with an 18” hole cut in the center 
Duct tape 
 
 How to: 
1.Using the four air filters construct a square making sure that the filter’s airflow direction points into the square. Secure the edges with duct tape. 
2. Place the box fan on top of the square, laying so that the airflow is pointing upward, attach to the square with duct tape, making sure to cover any gaps in the corners. 
3. Make a shroud by cutting an 18” diameter circle in the center of a 20” square piece of cardboard. 
4. Attach the shroud to the top of your fan using duct tape, making sure it’s centered. The shroud will reduce the backflow of air increasing efficiency! 
5. Plug in and enjoy clean air! 

So easy! 

 
Thank you 3M for partnering on this, it’s like you knew the way to my heart was through a good old fashioned DIY project! Not that I wasn’t a fan already, our 3M Filtrete furnace filters coincidently showed up just the other day and my house is covered in command strips ☺ I appreciate the opportunity to work with you!
